So it looks like the RIAA is beginning to crack down on illegal downloading of music. This article looks at a group of college kids that the RIAA chose to target. I agree that they were probably chosen due to their inability to put up much of a legal battle. And I think it's pretty outrageous to charge them $7.87 per song they downloaded too. I'm a big proponent of legal downloading due to the fact that I know what goes into releasing music: time, money, energy, etc. So, I think paying for it is well deserved (this view is with indie labels in mind). On the other hand, I really dislike major labels and feel like they make a huge deal out of illegal downloading taking away from their profits, but when you look at it on an album-by-album basis, it's really a drop in the bucket. If anyone is interested in legal downloading for cheap, emusic is a great resource.

Well, I was gonna writa a post about this documentary I saw last night called Friends of God and how evangelical christian groups, like this one, piss me off. But then I read this article today about a state-wide smoking ban. I have mixed feelings about this issue. One, I really like the idea of going to a bar and not coming home smelling like shit. Two, I really don't think it will cause a significant loss in business. In this article they state that bars in Austin are loosing on average $5700 per month. This sounds like a lot, but that breaks down to about $190 per day. Drinks in Austin aren't cheap, so let's say that a customer would spend $20 at the bar on any given night, that means the bar only looses around 9 customers a night. I'm sorry, but loosing 9 customers a night ain't gonna do shit to the bottom line. Plus, in business you constantly have to adjust, so if they were really worried about this $5700 they would either raise prices or find a way to drum up more business. Third, I believe everyone has a right not to breathe smokey air. The argument that non-smokers don't have to go to bars can just as easily be used smokers. You don't have to smoke. Now, with all of that said, this ban does have a down side to it. Mainly the fact that business owners don't have a say in part of their business. Bottom line, this was gonna happen eventually.
